Finalize the story's structure before it becomes passages. Two jobs, both additions
(the topology is frozen — nothing moves, nothing is deleted):

VISION: {{ vision.genre }}, {{ vision.tone }}. Themes: {{ vision.themes | join("; ") }}.

{% if needs %}
RESIDUE ARMS (required). Where a subplot's paths rejoin, the choice must still be
felt: the story visibly remembers whichever side the player took. For EACH
convergence below, write one flag-gated arm PER PATH — a beat that establishes
how the world feels for a player who took that path, placed just before the
storylines rejoin. 1-2 sentences, present tense, mood and memory, not plot — it
must not advance, reveal, or decide anything. When a path's memory deserves a
scene rather than a sentence, give its arm a "followup" beat (same gate; the
pair reads as one passage) — use it where the residue carries real weight, skip
it where a single breath is honest. When the memory could honestly sit two
ways — two textures of carrying the same truth — give the arm a "fork": a
second branch behind the same gate ({"id", "summary", "entities", "followup"
or omit}). The reader who made that upstream choice then gets a choice in how
to live with it; both branches rejoin where the arm does, and neither may
decide anything the other doesn't. Fork only where the split is honest — one
strong arm beats two thin ones.
{% for n in needs %}
- {{ n.dilemma.id }} (residue: light{% if n.need.world %}; in the world of {{ n.need.world }}{% endif %}) rejoins at {% for c in n.rejoin %}{{ c.id }} — "{{ c.summary }}"{% if not loop.last %} / {% endif %}{% endfor %}
{% for path, flags in n.need.path_flags.items() %}
  - path {{ path }} (its truth: {{ flags | join(", ") }}) arrives from: {{ n.tails[path].summary }}
{% endfor %}
{% endfor %}
Emit exactly one residue entry per path per convergence above — never two
entries for the same path. If one arm feels too small, do NOT add a second
entry: extend the single arm with a "followup" (a longer arm) or a "fork" (two
textures of the same choice behind the same gate). One entry per path, always.
Each entry:
{"dilemma", "path", "id": "beat:slug", "summary", "entities": [...],
"followup": {"id", "summary", "entities"} or omit,
"fork": {"id", "summary", "entities", "followup" or omit} or omit}; when a
convergence names a world, echo it as "world" exactly (a nested story rejoins
once per world — each world needs its own arms, colored by that world's
truth); when it names none, omit "world".
EVERY id here (arm, followup, fork) names a NEW beat the engine will create:
coin a fresh, unique "beat:slug" that no existing beat uses — never reuse or
lightly vary the rejoin or arrival beat ids shown above, and keep every id in
this proposal distinct from the others. A colliding id is rejected. Derive the
slug from the path or dilemma so it stays distinct, e.g. "beat:hand-locket-aftermath".
{% endif %}
{% include "_craft.j2" %}
{% include "_summary_brief.j2" %}
{% if reserve and (texture_sites or cadence) %}
RESERVED MATERIAL (advisory). Triage set these dilemmas aside as unwoven
feedstock — real material from this story's brainstorm. Where a texture
world or a false-branch arm wants substance, prefer grafting from them (a
place, a tension, a rumor they name) over inventing texture from nothing.
They stay unwoven: an arm may echo their material as texture, never
advance, reveal, or decide them.
{% for r in reserve %}
- {{ r.dilemma.question }} (stakes: {{ r.dilemma.why_it_matters }}{% if r.entities %}; touches {{ r.entities | join(", ") }}{% endif %})
{% endfor %}
{% endif %}
{% if texture_sites %}
TEXTURE WORLDS (required). Each stretch below runs several scenes with no
choice; lay a PARALLEL RENDERING over it — the SAME story events against
another backdrop. The difference may sit on any consequence-free axis:
where the events happen, by what road or means, in whose company, or in
the small facts of things and people along the way. The reader chooses a
rendering where the stretch begins and both converge exactly where it
ends: a different backdrop, never different consequences — nothing may
happen in one rendering that changes what is true after the convergence.
For EACH site: declare a one-line "premise" stating what differs, and
anchor it in a story element the beats, cast, or RESERVED MATERIAL above
already carry or clearly imply — the premise names that element and how
this rendering varies it. Then write exactly ONE beat per trunk beat, IN
ORDER: the same event the trunk beat carries, re-expressed with that
difference present. Summaries in plain declarative present tense (a brief
for the writer, never the prose).
{% for site in texture_sites %}
- site {{ site.index }} ({{ site.beats | length }} beats to mirror):
{% for b in site.beats %}
    {{ b.id }} — "{{ b.summary }}"
{% endfor %}
{% endfor %}
Each entry: {"site": the site index above, "premise": one line, "beats":
[{"id": "beat:slug", "summary", "entities": [...]}] — exactly one per trunk
beat, in order}. Every "id" names a NEW beat: coin fresh, unique
"beat:slug"s no existing beat uses (a colliding id is rejected); a
mechanical scheme is fine — site 0's beats as "beat:tw0-1", "beat:tw0-2",
and so on. The site counts
are MANDATORY: a proposal that skips a site, doubles one, or writes a
different beat count than the stretch is rejected whole.
{% endif %}
{% if cadence %}
FALSE BRANCHES (cadence). The story's real choices — its dilemmas — are
guaranteed elsewhere; these stretches run several scenes without ANY choice,
which reads as a book, not a game. The site counts below are computed from
the story's projected reading pace (a genuine-feeling decision every few
hundred words); fill each run's count, spreading the sites across its edges.
Two shapes, pick per site:
- a DIAMOND (2 arms): two flavors of the same forward motion, rejoining
  immediately — different textures (where you look, who you pass, what you
  overhear), never different consequences;
- a SIDETRACK (1 arm): an optional detour off the road that rejoins it —
  something the reader may stop to examine, or walk past. Declining is
  also a choice; use it where lingering is plausible.
An arm is one 1-sentence beat, plus an optional "followup" beat when its
flavor genuinely needs a breath more room.
{% for run in cadence %}
- run: {{ run.beats | join(" -> ") }}
  insert {{ run.edges | length }} site(s); suggested edges (scene seams — prefer these):
{% for before, after in run.edges %}
    {{ before }} -> {{ after }}
{% endfor %}
{% endfor %}
Each entry: {"before": beat id, "after": its successor in the same run,
"arms": [{"id": "beat:slug", "summary", "entities", "followup": {"id":
"beat:slug", "summary", "entities"} or omit}] — 2 arms for a diamond, 1 for a
sidetrack}. Every arm and followup "id" names a NEW beat: coin a fresh, unique
"beat:slug" no existing beat uses (a colliding id is rejected). Move a site
along its run only to avoid an ending's approach or a point of no return's
immediate aftermath.
The counts are MANDATORY, not advisory: a proposal that places fewer sites
on any run than that run's count above is rejected whole. Never return an
empty "false_branches" list while CADENCE lists runs — fill every run's
count, however flavorless a stretch seems; a plain diamond (look left /
look right) beats no choice at all.
{% endif %}
